What do you think the most common crime in your country is?

I would say that pickpocketing is one of the most prevalent crimes in Vietnam. One reason for this is that it is extremely difficult to detect, as these incidents tend to occur very quickly, often in crowded areas where it is easy for thieves to blend in.
As a result, victims usually do not realize what has happened until it is too late. I have come across several cases where people had their personal belongings stolen in public places. In more serious situations, some victims have even been injured during bag-snatching incidents.

Should the police in your country be stricter or less strict?

I don’t believe the main issue is whether the police should be stricter or more lenient. In Vietnam, I think the police generally perform their duties quite effectively.

In my view, the bigger concern lies within the legal framework itself. If the penalties are not severe enough, they may fail to act as a strong deterrent, which can lead to people becoming less mindful of the law.

At the same time, I think it is important for police officers to exercise a certain degree of discretion when dealing with different situations, as not all cases should be handled in exactly the same way.

Overall, I would argue that improving the legal system and ensuring consistent enforcement would be more effective than simply making the police stricter.

Is your country a safe country?

Yes, overall I would consider Vietnam to be a relatively safe country. There is a well-established legal system, and laws are generally enforced effectively, which helps maintain social order.

One key factor contributing to this is the strict control over weapons, as civilians are not permitted to carry them. This significantly reduces the likelihood of serious violent incidents.

Additionally, there is a visible police presence in many public areas, especially on the streets, which helps regulate traffic and ensures public safety. This gives people a sense of security in their everyday lives.

Of course, no country is completely crime-free, but compared to many others, I would say Vietnam is a relatively safe place to live.

Have you ever seen a crime?
Yes, I have. I once witnessed a bag-snatching incident where a young man attempted to steal a woman’s handbag while she was riding her motorbike. The whole situation happened so quickly that people around couldn’t react in time.

The woman lost control and fell onto the road, and she was dragged for several meters before the thief let go. Although she managed to keep her bag, she ended up with multiple bruises and scratches. Her head also hit the ground, but fortunately, she was wearing a helmet, which prevented any serious injury.

Do you think criminals can change?
Yes, I definitely think criminals can change. Committing a crime doesn’t necessarily mean that a person will continue down that path for the rest of their life. In fact, many people are able to turn their lives around after going through rehabilitation.

I believe that no one is born a criminal. Factors such as upbringing, living conditions, and social environment can strongly influence a person’s behavior.

If former offenders are given proper support, such as education, job opportunities, and guidance, they can reintegrate into society and become productive members of the community.

Is shoplifting common in your country

Yes, I would say shoplifting does occur in Vietnam, although it may not be extremely common. In recent years, with the rise of social media, many shop owners have shared incidents online to raise awareness.
In some cases, thieves pretend to be regular customers and secretly hide items in their bags or jackets before leaving without paying. Shop owners often only realize what has happened after reviewing security camera footage, which can be quite frustrating for them.

What kind of people shoplift and what kinds of things do they steal

I don't think shoplifting is limited to a particular type of person. While some people may assume that it is mainly committed by those from low-income backgrouns, I don't entirely agree with that view. In my opinion, it has more to do with a person's value, upbringing, and self-control rather than their financial situation.
In fact, even people from wealthier backgrounds can engage in shoplifting if they lack a strong sense of responsibility or act out of impulse or greed.
As for the items that were usually stolen, they tend to be small, high-value, and easy to conceal, such as cosmetics, accessories, or eletronic gadgets. These items can be quickly hidden and are often easy to resell, which makes them attractive targets for shoplifters.
